Drawing from imagination takes many skills. First comes learning FORCE, Form and Shape.  Then anatomy. It is a long bridge to cross to move from reference to using one's drawing skills to imagine figures that function the way they are designed to. Also try to keep in mind silhouette so the pose you create stays clear.  Watch FORCE Friday on the YouTube Channel FORCE with Mike Mattesi for more information on Drawing from Imagination.  To deepen your skills, check out DrawingFORCE.com.

During my time at Walt Disney Feature Animation, we were trained to notice tangents and remove them from drawings for the animation. At times an inbetween may unfortunately create a tangent and attempt to flatten a drawing.  This could occur in a background as well, diminishing depth. If you desire to flatten your work, use tangents.  Want depth? Create overlaps giving depth priority to one object over another.

To learn how to draw, visit DrawingFORCE.com and sign up for one on one mentorship today!

FORCE Figure Drawing, Two Day Workshop with Mike Mattesi in Brooklyn, NY! 
Finally solve how to bring dynamic FORCE, fluid line, volume and appealing shape to your work! This two day, in person workshop with Mike Mattesi will include a dynamic figure model, live demos, group and individual feedback. In two days you will learn how to draw with FORCE, bring into three dimensional drawing and discover how it all gets combined with appealing FORCE Shape!
Receive Free Bonuses worth over $600

Details:
Only 12 Seats available. Guaranteed, personalized instruction!
Dates: Oct 21st and 22nd
Schedule: 10am-1pm. Lunch. 2pm-5pm
Location: Brooklyn, NY
Cost: $1125

Day One: What you’ll learn
Master FORCE Line and its meaning. 
Experience three exercises that you can use to quickly improve your line.
How to Find and Draw FORCES and Rhythms
Learn the simple FORCE templates that will direct FORCES and generate rhythm
How to bring Gravity into your work
Two approaches of skating and chopping
A new way of looking at and using angles
What to be thinking about while drawing
Directional and Applied FORCES
The use of the arrow
Animator’s tricks for drawing the figure
Metaphors to power up your work
Keep proportions without losing dynamism
#1 reason for stiff figures and how to remove it
The Three steps to drawing
The importance of hierarchy and how it’s used in FORCE Drawing

Day Two: What you’ll learn
How to see perspective relative to the model
Putting the model in a box
Four point perspective and the limits of one point
Recognizing turning edges and how to find them
Cross contours
How to bring FORCE into three dimensions
Studying masters to learn sculpting
The European vacation Metaphor
Good and bad shapes
The FORCE Shape
FORCE blobs and the octopus
Most common FORCE shapes found in the body.
The power of tone
The super power of shape for depth
How to draw a full figure in thirty seconds.

Well, here is the last of the NYC Comic Con hall of fame meet and greets. All fist images per artist are tagged if you want to visit their instagram account. 
1. Fist up is Jorge Jimenez. I just shared with you his work on a FORCE Friday session on YouTube when we spoke about rendering. I think Jorge lives and breathes comics more than any other comic artist I know. From his amazing physique, to his film quality Super Man costume and comics decorated house, they all relate to comics!
2. Alexander Lozano: Amazing work full of FORCE! Not only does he illustrate breath taking cover work but also creates illustrations for the film industry. Just discovered him (student James Z rec) so it was a pleasant surprise to meet him in person! He mentioned how the renaissance is a great inspiration for his work. 
3. Klaus Janson is best known for his huge contributions with Frank Miller on Dare Devil and The Dark Knight (ironically, the book that inspired me to go to art school)! He mentored me for a year after I graduated from college and I learned so much from Klaus. Great catching up and seeing him again!
4. Adam Hughes! Profound. Has been at the top of the field for over 25 years! Adam is amazing at creating appeal. He brought strong attention to Wonder Woman back in the 1990's. He is also known for his gorgeous, Audrey Hepburn like Cat Woman! 
It was a great con and I'll be back next year. More to come with video interviews that will be published on YouTube at FORCE with Mike Mattesi.

This snapshot is from a mentorship meeting today. The drawing on the left, I illustrated to share with the student specific areas of force in the back, and how it moves down into the shoulders and arms. To the right, you can find the reference and some of the student’s work, and the metaphorical illustration they created of waterfalls. I believe that when you have interesting ideas to accomplish in your drawing, they improve the experience and the drawing as well. So, looking for comparisons between the pose and other ideas brings forth a much more informed and dynamic drawing #forcedrawing #howtodraw #dynamicstretching #linedrawing #mikemattesi

I tech four point perspective. This grid is closest to how the human eyes sees.  Your pupil with be at the center of the grid. Practice creating boxes in the grid to help you develop your sense of angles that create a box in different locations. #perspective #perspectivedrawing #howtodraw #drawingtutorials
